Protesting women in their hundreds staged a road walk against rape in Adamawa state. The women carried placards Thursday, lamented the  increasing rate of gender base violence. Aminu Iya Abbas, Speaker of the state House of Assembly, said he and his colleagues in the rest of the Northeast were planning a law to provide for castration of rapists. The anti-rape protest by Adamawa women which took the form of a road walk, took the women across streets of the state capital, Yola. The women, as well as male activists, staged the road walk singing anti-rape songs and holding placards expressing their grievances. “No girl, no mother, no future,” “There is no excuse for rape,” “Rape must cease,” the placards proclaimed. The protest which was organised by the Ministry of Women Affairs and Social Development, was strengthened by the Office of the Wife of the Governor. The governor’s wife, Hajia Lami Fintiri, was personally on hand and was on the procession across most of the streets covered. The event ended at the state House of Assembly complex where the speaker was addressed by the Commissioner of Women Affairs and Social Development, Mrs Lami Ganda. The Commissioner told the Assembly that her ministry organised the anti-rape protest because it felt compelled to act against rape, which she said was becoming alarming. She said, “We continue to be burdened by incidents of rape and we have become restless, hence our coming out today to say we have had more than enough.” She appealed for a law to stop the constant rape of women and girls across the state. Responding, Speaker Aminu Iya Abbas said although there is a law prescribing a 21-year jail term, the Assembly was working in conjunction with others in the Northeast to legislate a stiffer penalty. 